	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2984621255" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hey Noby!</p><p>Yes and no :). A lot of the work we did was initial setup. So if you wanted to cache in a different route/controller, you wouldn't need to do much work at all: (A) add a new entry in config.yml under "doctrine_cache" and "providers" then (B) fetch that service in a controller and use it to cache. Not too much work.</p><p>But also, you likely won't need to cache very often. Of course, it depends on your application, but, for example, the vast majority of the routes/controllers on our site don't have any caching: it's just fast enough.</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
